From: Micheal Waltz <micheal@ecliptik.com>
Date: Wed, 29 Apr 2026 12:27:55 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] =?UTF-8?q?[DOSKUTSU]=20dos:=20Phase=209=20wave=2016.3=20p?=
 =?UTF-8?q?atch=200031=20=E2=80=94=20LFB=20sentinel=20test?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Wave 16.3 confirmed bottom-strip-black persists with LFB engaged via
patch 0030's force-LFB override. The bug is NOT banked-mode-specific;
something on the g2k Cirrus + UNIVBE 6.70 caps either the aperture
itself or the display controller's scan region at the bank-0 boundary.

Two surviving hypotheses:

  H-a "LFB aperture lies past 64KB": writes to LFB+>=65536 land in the
       aperture but the chip never propagates them to VRAM (or routes
       them to the wrong VRAM region). Readback through the SAME
       aperture returns garbage / zeros / pre-write value.

  H-b "writes land in VRAM but display controller doesn't scan past
       64KB": writes round-trip cleanly through the aperture (data IS
       in VRAM), but the display generator's scan-out region caps at
       the bank-0 boundary regardless of pitch / height. VRAM is
       correct; only the displayed picture truncates.

This patch disambiguates: write a known 16-byte sentinel pattern
(0xDEADBEEF repeating) via the SAME LFB pointer SDL3-DOS uses for
production writes (fb_state.vram_ptr at line ~1041 / 1072), then
read it back through the SAME pointer. Sample 5 offsets:

  LFB+0       — control (top-of-screen, must round-trip cleanly)
  LFB+65535   — last byte of bank 0 (boundary control)
  LFB+65536   — first byte past bank-0 boundary (the suspected hot zone)
  LFB+76799   — last byte of displayed frame (320×240 - 1)
  LFB+131072  — well past boundary, into off-screen VRAM

For each: snapshot original 16 bytes, write sentinel, read back, log
match=<0|1>, restore original — so the displayed picture isn't
corrupted by the diagnostic.

One-shot fire on first flip when LFB is engaged (static fired flag).
If the hypothesis-(a) aperture is broken, it's broken on every flush
— single-shot is enough and we don't pay per-frame overhead. Same
single-shot pattern as patch 0029 (bank-1 offset fix) one-shot logging.

Env-gated by SDL_HINT_DOSKUTSU_LFB_SENTINEL=1 (strict "1" match per
CLAUDE.md DOSKUTSU env-var convention; default OFF so production
iters aren't impacted). Pairs with patch 0030's
SDL_HINT_DOSKUTSU_FORCE_LFB=1 to engage LFB on the Cirrus auto-disable
fingerprint.

Interpretation playbook (next-iter fix path):

  match=1 at LFB+65536 → H-b confirmed. Aperture works; the chip is
         selectively NOT scanning past 64KB. Investigate VBE 0x4F07
         display-start, pitch fields, or a Cirrus-specific scan-cap
         register the BIOS doesn't expose. Possible escape hatches:
         320×200 mode (fits in 64KB), 4bpp planar, smaller logical
         surface.

  match=0 at LFB+65536 → H-a confirmed. Aperture broken past 64KB.
         Investigate alternate apertures (some Cirrus chips expose a
         separate "extended" aperture), Cirrus chip-direct LFB-window-
         base register writes, or fall back to banked + alternate
         Cirrus-specific bank-switch primitive. DO NOT push LFB; revert
         to banked + chase H-C from patch 0028's playbook.

  match=1 everywhere (all 5 offsets round-trip) and bottom-strip-black
         persists → H-b confirmed for the entire post-bank-0 region.
         Display is the bottleneck, not the write path.

Side-effects: writes 16 bytes at each of 5 offsets into the aperture,
then restores the original bytes. On DOSBox-X (LFB known-good) the
restore makes the diagnostic visually invisible. On the g2k Cirrus
where the aperture may be broken at some offsets, the "restore" write
goes through the same aperture so any visual artifact is bounded to
those 16-byte regions for ≤1 frame and is masked by the existing
bottom-strip-black bug at offsets ≥65536.

Sample offsets are within the DPMI-mapped VRAM region (mapping size =
DOSVESA_GetVESATotalMemory(), ≥1024 KB on this Cirrus per the modeset
log). All reads/writes are safe.

Existing diagnostic patches (0027 audit, 0028 banked sentinel, 0029
offset rewrite, 0030 force-LFB override) remain in place as passive
observers so a single iter capture can correlate banked-side and
LFB-side behaviour.

Per docs/BOOT.md convention every new env var is documented in the
"Diagnostic / development options" subsection. The LFB sentinel is
dev-only, not user-facing.

Local-only patch per workspace policy. Never PR'd upstream.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c | 120 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 120 insertions(+)

diff --git a/src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c b/src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c
index 6c34ad55d..3486258c1 100644
--- a/src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c
+++ b/src/video/dos/SDL_dosframebuffer.c
@@ -1279,6 +1279,126 @@ bool DOSVESA_UpdateWindowFramebuffer(SDL_VideoDevice *device, SDL_Window *window
             }
         }
 
+        // DOSKUTSU patch 0031 (wave 16.3 LFB sentinel — bottom-strip-black
+        // disambiguation when LFB is engaged via patch 0030's force-LFB
+        // override). The wave 16.3 result confirmed bottom-strip-black
+        // persists with LFB engaged on the g2k Cirrus + UNIVBE 6.70 — so
+        // the bug is NOT banked-mode-specific. Two surviving hypotheses:
+        //
+        //   H-a "LFB aperture lies past 64KB": writes to LFB+>=65536 land
+        //        in the aperture but the chip never propagates them to
+        //        VRAM (or routes them to the wrong VRAM region). Readback
+        //        through the SAME aperture returns garbage / zeros / the
+        //        pre-write value.
+        //
+        //   H-b "writes land in VRAM but display controller doesn't scan
+        //        past 64KB": writes round-trip cleanly through the
+        //        aperture (data IS in VRAM), but the display generator's
+        //        scan-out region caps at the bank-0 boundary regardless
+        //        of the configured fb pitch / height. VRAM is correct;
+        //        only the displayed picture truncates.
+        //
+        // Disambiguation: write a known sentinel via the SAME LFB pointer
+        // SDL3-DOS uses for production writes (fb_state.vram_ptr), then
+        // read it back through the SAME pointer. Sample 5 offsets:
+        //
+        //   LFB+0       — control (top-of-screen, must round-trip cleanly)
+        //   LFB+65535   — last byte of bank 0 (control for the boundary)
+        //   LFB+65536   — first byte past the bank-0 boundary (the hot zone)
+        //   LFB+76799   — last byte of the displayed frame (320×240×1bpp - 1)
+        //   LFB+131072  — well past the boundary, into off-screen VRAM
+        //
+        // Restore each region's original 16 bytes after the test so the
+        // displayed picture isn't corrupted by the diagnostic. One-shot
+        // (static fired flag) — if H-a is true it's true on every flush,
+        // so single-shot is enough and we don't pay per-frame overhead.
+        //
+        // Interpretation playbook (next-iter fix path):
+        //   match=1 at LFB+65536 → H-b confirmed. Aperture works; the
+        //          chip is selectively NOT scanning past 64KB. Investigate
+        //          VBE 0x4F07 display-start, pitch fields, or a Cirrus-
+        //          specific scan-cap register the BIOS doesn't expose.
+        //          Possible escape hatches: 320×200 mode (fits in 64KB),
+        //          4bpp planar, or a smaller logical surface.
+        //   match=0 at LFB+65536 → H-a confirmed. Aperture is broken past
+        //          64KB. Investigate alternate apertures (some Cirrus
+        //          chips expose a separate "extended" aperture), Cirrus
+        //          chip-direct LFB-window-base register writes, or fall
+        //          back to the banked path with an alternate Cirrus-
+        //          specific bank-switch primitive (chip register vs VBE).
+        //          DO NOT push LFB; revert to banked + chase H-C from
+        //          patch 0028's interpretation playbook.
+        //   match=1 at +0 / +65535 / +76799 / +131072 (i.e., everywhere)
+        //          → aperture works at all sampled offsets. If
+        //          bottom-strip-black persists, reads/writes are clean
+        //          but display is the bottleneck — H-b confirmed for
+        //          ALL of post-bank-0 region.
+        //
+        // Env-gated by SDL_HINT_DOSKUTSU_LFB_SENTINEL=1 (strict "1" match,
+        // default OFF) per CLAUDE.md DOSKUTSU env-var convention. Default
+        // OFF so no impact on production fps measurement when the iter
+        // isn't deliberately running this diagnostic. The sample offsets
+        // are within the DPMI-mapped VRAM region (mapping size =
+        // DOSVESA_GetVESATotalMemory(), which is ≥1024 KB on the target
+        // Cirrus per modeset log) so all reads/writes are safe.
+        if (!fb_state.use_dosmemput && fb_state.vram_ptr) {
+            static int  _lfb_sentinel_enabled_cached = -1;
+            static bool _lfb_sentinel_fired = false;
+            if (_lfb_sentinel_enabled_cached == -1) {
+                const char *e = SDL_getenv("SDL_HINT_DOSKUTSU_LFB_SENTINEL");
+                _lfb_sentinel_enabled_cached = (e && e[0] == '1' && e[1] == 0) ? 1 : 0;
+            }
+            if (_lfb_sentinel_enabled_cached && !_lfb_sentinel_fired) {
+                _lfb_sentinel_fired = true;
+                static const Uint32 lfb_sentinel_offsets[5] = {
+                    0u, 65535u, 65536u, 76799u, 131072u,
+                };
+                static const Uint8 lfb_sentinel_pat[16] = {
+                    0xDE, 0xAD, 0xBE, 0xEF, 0xDE, 0xAD, 0xBE, 0xEF,
+                    0xDE, 0xAD, 0xBE, 0xEF, 0xDE, 0xAD, 0xBE, 0xEF,
+                };
+                for (int s = 0; s < 5; s++) {
+                    const Uint32 off = lfb_sentinel_offsets[s];
+                    Uint8 *dp = fb_state.vram_ptr + off;
+                    Uint8 saved[16];
+                    Uint8 readback[16];
+                    // Snapshot the original 16 bytes BEFORE the write so we
+                    // can restore them — keeps the displayed picture clean
+                    // (no garbage pixels from the sentinel diagnostic).
+                    SDL_memcpy(saved, dp, 16);
+                    // Write sentinel via the SAME LFB pointer SDL3-DOS uses
+                    // in the production write path at line ~1041 / 1072
+                    // (SDL_memcpy(fb_state.vram_ptr, ...)). If the aperture
+                    // is broken at this offset, the write goes nowhere or
+                    // somewhere wrong.
+                    SDL_memcpy(dp, lfb_sentinel_pat, 16);
+                    // Read back through the SAME pointer. If readback ==
+                    // sentinel_pat, the aperture round-trips at this offset.
+                    // If readback != sentinel_pat, the aperture is broken
+                    // here — the data went somewhere we can't read back.
+                    SDL_memcpy(readback, dp, 16);
+                    const int match = (SDL_memcmp(lfb_sentinel_pat, readback, 16) == 0) ? 1 : 0;
+                    doskutsu_dbg_log(
+                        "WAVE16-3-LFB-SENTINEL @off=%lu: write_via=lfb_vram_ptr "
+                        "read_via=lfb_vram_ptr match=%d "
+                        "wrote=%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x "
+                        "readback=%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x",
+                        (unsigned long)off, match,
+                        lfb_sentinel_pat[0],  lfb_sentinel_pat[1],  lfb_sentinel_pat[2],  lfb_sentinel_pat[3],
+                        lfb_sentinel_pat[4],  lfb_sentinel_pat[5],  lfb_sentinel_pat[6],  lfb_sentinel_pat[7],
+                        lfb_sentinel_pat[8],  lfb_sentinel_pat[9],  lfb_sentinel_pat[10], lfb_sentinel_pat[11],
+                        lfb_sentinel_pat[12], lfb_sentinel_pat[13], lfb_sentinel_pat[14], lfb_sentinel_pat[15],
+                        readback[0],  readback[1],  readback[2],  readback[3],
+                        readback[4],  readback[5],  readback[6],  readback[7],
+                        readback[8],  readback[9],  readback[10], readback[11],
+                        readback[12], readback[13], readback[14], readback[15]);
+                    // Restore original bytes via the SAME pointer so the
+                    // displayed region returns to the post-flush state.
+                    SDL_memcpy(dp, saved, 16);
+                }
+            }
+        }
+
         // Page flipping is only used with the nearptr LFB path. The banked
         // dosmemput path always writes to page 0 (the visible page) and
         // accepts tearing, avoiding a BIOS call.
-- 
